Putting it together, the hardened service.

Let us combine everything into a single compose service. The image is pinned by digest, so the deploy is byte-identical every time. It runs as a non-root user. Its root filesystem is read-only, with small in-memory mounts for the few paths that need to be writable. All capabilities are dropped, and only the one needed to bind a low port is added back. No-new-privileges is on, so there is no set-user-I-D escalation. The database password comes in as a mounted secret file rather than an environment variable, and the app is told to read it from that file path. The service sits on a back-end network, restarts unless stopped, and has a healthcheck. At the bottom of the file, the secret is defined from a local file, and the network from a bridge driver.

On the registry side, the image this references was built from a multi-stage dockerfile, producing a slim, no-toolchain runtime. It is pinned by digest so the deploy is reproducible, signed so admission controllers can verify its origin, accompanied by a software bill of materials so scanners can audit its packages, and accompanied by a provenance attestation so auditors can verify the whole build chain.

That is the full picture. None of it is mandatory, and all of it is achievable in a continuous-integration pipeline of a few hundred lines of configuration. The certification exam in notebook ten tests a subset of these, non-root, capabilities, secrets, and signing, and those happen to be the same things real auditors ask about. So hardening is not a box-ticking exercise. Each dial you turn closes a concrete escalation path, and turning all of them is what a production-grade container posture looks like.
